<font color="#FF0000">DIALOGUE</font><br>
<tt>Mon Dec  9 21:07:43 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Whether we went to the war or not, the most important thing was, I think, to have answered our own conscience as we knew it at that time. None of us really new what we were getting into. We didn't really have the fodder to make an informed decision. I didn't have the courage to go to jail or Canada so went to the war instead. Is Clinton just a present day representation for the guys who went us there? Guys like Kennedy, Johnston, Nixon, Rostow,...I'm sorry they're dead because they should be cleaning bedpans in VA hospitals. McNamara &amp; is still with us. Where is the accountability for the waste in human lives? We know why Americans died in WWII and Korea. I have not heard a good reason yet for Viet Nam. The most memorable lesson in basic training came from the mouth of the DI &quot;What's patriotism, dying for your country? No, making the other guy die for his country. That's patriotism&quot;. This is a direct quote my brothers.<br>
 Judging from the final arithmetic of the war, it would appear that we were exceedingly patriotic, the VC &amp; NVA losses were (?) 1 to 1.5 million combat dead, is this true?? (not including the bystanders), and what good did all of this patriotism do anybody? The American war in Viet Nam was not something we just stumbled into. A lot of civilian leaders worked hard for a long time to get us into that deal. Our civilian leadership did not heed the lessons of the French. At 18 years of age we did not know that the French had fought and lost their war in Viet Nam for the same reasons we eventually had to leave. Our leadership underestimated their own stupidity and the VC &amp; NVA capacity for dying. <br><br>
Thank you for this web site. It is a beauticul thing. We need to keep talking.<br>
On a different note, something that popped up a couple of years back...<br><br>
Apology to canine companions:<br><br>
Main street Phu Loi<br>
Loop road circumnavigating the airstrip<br>
For landing takeoff craft of occupiers<br>
Japanese, French, Americans.<br><br>
Used car salesman Nixon <br>
Finally reads the writing on the wall<br>
We are leaving<br>
But dogs read only between the lines.<br><br>
Mascots of spirits still guarding<br>
Vacant hooches of a stand-down ghost town<br>
Rooted motionless but for head turning<br>
As I stroll by.<br><br>
Eyes -- Wishing I was some missing friend<br>
Ears -- Semaphores of distress.<br>
Abandoned by two legged walking upright buddies<br>
Left behind by your forced-to-move-on-under-orders human.<br><br>
Did you end up in the borrow pit?<br>
Mercifully dispatched by lovingly well placed rounds?<br>
Or in a local stew pot?<br>
I was lucky, they let me send my pooch home.<br><br>
LMD,  Spec 4, Phu Loi, 1971-1972
